						               													<description>Each &amp;quot;Ego&amp;quot; card displays 4 situations and 4 attitudes for each situation to choose..&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In his turn player chooses a card and reads aloud the situation in which it is located and the four attitudes that are offered to A, B, C and D. He chooses an attitude for this situation for him.&amp;#10;All other players try to guess together what the reader would have done in this situation and choose one attitude (A,B,C,D)&amp;#10;If they guess the correct attitude the current player had chosen then the player keeps the card and the place before him. If the choice is different, the player loses this card.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;When all the 'ego' cards was used, the game is over. The winner is the player with the most points (cards).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;EGO is primarily a game of communication. It can be played in a more free, not counting the points. The player is faced with a situation must secretly choose his attitude and sincerely address this situation (among the options set out on his map 'ego'). He has no interest in lying. Other players will then guess what he or she would do in this situation, given their own idea of &amp;#226;&amp;#128;&amp;#139;&amp;#226;&amp;#128;&amp;#139;the person. Finally, the answers are revealed and compared. The comments will then rife about the personality of sometimes surprising each other.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
